node.text: Such a rad time with an awesome group of peoples. The @GridExperience definitely sets the bar (and sets it pretty high) for me when it comes to indoor karting. Combine that with a this crew of friends and fam: Jeremy McGrath, Sage Kotsenburg, Zak Hale, Davey Coombs (founder of Racer X), Zac Mertens (of Hoonigan Racing), etc. - plus Jett and Hunter Lawrence were two of the top three fastest of the night (same positions as they finished in the 250 Main of the Supercross race this past weekend!). Jeremy’s daughter (Rhowan) and my daughter (Lia) both had two of the top lap five times also (yep, we’re proud Dads!). Good times!

node.title: Rad time karting at The Grid Experience with friends and fam.

node.text: This weekend will be my first competitive drive in a Subaru since 2009. With only one proper day of testing before @AlexGelsomino and I show up this weekend to the @OlympusRally (3rd round of the @ARA_Rally Championship) it will be interesting to see how quickly I can get fully comfortable in it and run at full tilt. But so far, the car looks (livery by @ItsALiving) and feels (built and prepped by Vermont SportsCar) great! Check out this week's episode on my YouTube channel (link in bio) for the livery reveal, and to hear about all our plans for a wild year! #gravelslayingaction

node.text: Here’s another AINT CARE moment from the vault: @AlexGelsomino and I lost our front right side wheel midway through Stage 3 (of Oregon Trail Rally in 2013) due to a freak mechanical failure. We kept the hammer down and finished that stage, and then continued on to run another full stage on just 3 wheels, rather than settling for a DNF. We finished the race 2nd overall - all because we were able to drive through this #AINTCARE situation!

node.text: AIN’T CARE, rally cross example: after qualifying first, winning each of the heats, and leading the first 5 laps of the Final in the 2012 GRC race in Las Vegas, the ECU/control panel in my race car caught fire. I continued the race for as long as I could, but the fumes from the fire were starting to burn my lungs. I led and raced for as long as I could but eventually had to stop. I truly tried to AIN’T CARE as long as I could, but wasn’t willing to die for the win. 🤷‍♂️ #AINTCARE #pressonregardless

node.text: A helicopter is very important for a Trophy Truck team. From safety (such as: catching a bike or a crashed competitor ahead on course) to filming (because the trucks race over hundreds of miles and that is hard to shoot with just cameras on the ground). Here’s a few shots of it in use as we tested and filmed last week. #WhoopocalypseNow

node.text: While out testing the Trophy Truck with Jax Redline and his team in CA, my buddy @ashthorp came out to see one of the vehicles in action that he has digitally rendered. Not only is Ash a wizard when it comes to the digital world (his renders of this truck are incredible), but he’s also very talented with a camera! Not bad shots for this dude’s first time shooting a Trophy Truck, right?? I also took him for a ride-a-long, and his reactions were priceless. Thanks for the rad shots, Ash! #digitalwizard #WhoopocalypseNow

node.text: This beast absolutely rips!! @alexgelsomino and I spent the last two days smashing whoops, catching air, and learning the intricacies of this 1100 hp truck - all in the 120 degree heat of Plaster City, CA. Great to get some real testing time in it - because the next stop in my Baja 1000 prep is next week: the “Vegas to Reno” race! Photo: @ashthorp. #WhoopocalypseNow #TrophyTruck
